{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/sepsis/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"25449018-76ee-5a28-ba72-210726d864df","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 4f5b8849-7167-432c-93ed-aa4c00f34d70 --><h2>What causes it?</h2><!-- end field 4f5b8849-7167-432c-93ed-aa4c00f34d70 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f5243ddd-c818-4804-b654-aa4c00f34d38 --><!-- begin field 560f9607-67f2-4dab-8e31-aa4c00f34d70 --><p><strong>The exact pathophysiology of sepsis is not known, but it is thought to be a multifactorial response to an infecting pathogen that may be amplified by host factors (such as genetics, age, and co-morbidities), the pathogen (type, virulence, and burden), and the environment </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Freitag, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Singer, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Cecconi, 2018</a>]<strong>.</strong></p><ul><li>The mechanism of cell injury is not fully understood, but it is theorized that immune and coagulation systems are switched on by infection and cause dysfunction of one or more organs with variable severity [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Freitag, 2016</a>].<ul><li>It is thought this involves the early activation of both pro-inflammatory responses (leading to cellular and tissue damage) and anti-inflammatory responses (leading to immunosuppression). Resulting tissue hypoxia, mitochondrial dysfunction, macrovascular and microvascular dysfunction, and apoptosis are thought to be mediators of organ dysfunction [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Gauer, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Singer, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Cecconi, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Poston, 2019</a>].</li></ul></li><li>The most common sites of infection leading to sepsis are the respiratory, gastrointestinal, renal and genitourinary tracts, as well as blood, skin, soft tissue, bone and joint sources [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Gauer, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Cecconi, 2018</a>].<ul><li>Some studies cite an equal prevalence of Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacterial infections in people with sepsis, particularly <em>Staphylococcus aureus</em>, Pseudomonas species, and <em>Escherichia coli</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Rhodes, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Cecconi, 2018</a>].</li><li>In children, <em>Neisseria meningitides</em> and <em>Haemophilus influenzae</em> may also be involved [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Plunkett, 2015</a>].</li><li>Rarely, fungal, viral, or parasitic infections are causative [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Gauer, 2013</a>].</li><li>In about one-third of people with sepsis, no causative pathogen is identified [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Rhodes, 2017</a>].</li><li>About 80% of hospital-treated sepsis cases originate from community-acquired infection [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/references/\">Cecconi, 2018</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 560f9607-67f2-4dab-8e31-aa4c00f34d70 --><!-- end item f5243ddd-c818-4804-b654-aa4c00f34d38 -->","topic":{"id":"6934ac75-4c45-5f2f-8c9a-2d8851f1adf5","topicId":"eab5610a-80e3-49d5-ac25-aa0600a5625f","topicName":"Sepsis","slug":"sepsis","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2020","chapters":[{"id":"21403d5c-7f6a-58f8-a754-f80facfcc7b7","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"01bfd22f-a788-595c-9d77-4f15e7d21471","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8280962c-6cb2-53a1-8eed-ec18c19db62a","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"02ea2408-9b6e-5954-a3bc-8305ad7c2b3d","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"c2a838a7-45f2-5a2b-8e94-13f83b057517","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"a1a6b520-0d3e-5568-8fcf-e882ce604048","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"a9d2a1af-b338-5209-93b4-bddc7b6b5cbd","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"b2606ff0-0e97-55b2-83e3-4b0c5d0a2be2","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"3c4a84a7-c8f8-551b-bf15-639adaa8882d","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"af6a0131-ac12-5bf9-9ae2-5a74b2adbde7","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"379dd412-6848-5408-bbec-b555f59bfc67","slug":"qipp","fullItemName":"QIPP"},{"id":"cae1293c-e888-54e5-a1dd-6f9b76935048","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"e59cb5ea-715e-5c86-a9eb-1321bb0a362f","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"6ca10715-009f-5d48-ae98-5f1104993328","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"25449018-76ee-5a28-ba72-210726d864df","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes"},{"id":"2e720b24-f767-5b2a-98e1-3cac09695ebc","slug":"risk-fa